          From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia                            Jump to:     navigation,      search               This article is an orphan, as no other articles link to it. Please introduce links to this page from related articles; try the Find link tool for suggestions. (November 2012)   Sir Henry Lindo Ferguson CMG CStJ (7 April 1858 – 22 January 1948) was a New Zealand ophthalmologist, university professor and medical school dean. He was born in London, England on 7 April 1858.[1] In 1935, he was awarded the King George V Silver Jubilee Medal.[2] References[edit]   ^ Clair, Rex Wright-St. "Henry Lindo Ferguson". Dictionary of New Zealand Biography. Ministry for Culture and Heritage. Retrieved December 2011.  ^ "Official jubilee medals". Evening Post. 6 May 1935. p. 4. Retrieved 2 July 2013.        This biographical article about a New Zealand academic is a stub. You can help Wikipedia by expanding it.   v t e          This biography related to medicine in New Zealand is a stub. You can help Wikipedia by expanding it.   v t e                         Retrieved from "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Henry_Lindo_Ferguson&oldid=721246894"          Categories: 1858 births1948 deathsNew Zealand academicsNew Zealand medical doctorsPeople from LondonEnglish emigrants to New ZealandUniversity of Otago facultyNew Zealand ophthalmologistsCompanions of the Order of St Michael and St GeorgeKnights BachelorNew Zealand knightsCommanders of the Order of St JohnNew Zealand academic biography stubsNew Zealand medical biography stubsHidden categories: Orphaned articles from November 2012All orphaned articlesAll stub articles            
